<body bgcolor=white lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<p align=center style='text-align:center'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:18.0pt'>Course Syllabus<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p align=center style='text-align:center'>CompSci154 - Computer Design Lab</p>

<p align=center style='text-align:center'>Prof. A. Veidenbaum</p>

<p>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>

<p><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Prerequisites</b>:
CompSci151 (or equivalent). CompSci152 is also recommended, concurrent
registration in 152 OK<o:p></o:p></p>

<p><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Optional
Textbook</b>: Andrew Rushton, &quot;VHDL for Logic Synthesis&quot;, McGraw Hill
Publishing Co </p>

<p>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>

<p><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>COURSE
OVERVIEW<o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p>This course is an introduction to computer system design. It examines a
detailed design of major processor units, such as the register file, ALU, PC
unit, memory interface, and control unit and how they work together to execute
programs. It introduces students to a syntesizeable subset of a hardware
description language VHLD and teaches students how to design and verify a
processor using the language. The use of CAD tools, design synthesis and
verification are also introduced. Each student designs and verifies a complete
processor that can execute a subset of MIPS ISA. </p>

<p>The course assumes the knowledge of the basic elements used in designing a
computer system, such as combinational and sequential logic, and uses them to
design an ALU, register file, memory, and the basic control for these
subsystems (some of these concepts will be reviewed). In addition to teaching
students the design skills, the course helps students to better understand how
a processor works.</p>

<p>The course deals with design at the logic level, not circuit
(transistor-level) design. Using CAD tools students produce working hardware
using FPGA technology. </p>

<p><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p>After taking this course, you should be able to:<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:27.0pt'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal;mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>- Better understand how a processor works <o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:27.0pt'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>- Describe computer components using a hardware description language - <o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:27.0pt'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>- Design all major blocks of a simple processor <o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:27.0pt'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>- Design a control unit and make a complete processor <o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:27.0pt'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>- Simulate program execution on your design <o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:27.0pt'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal;mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>- Learn how to verify design correctness <o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:27.0pt'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal;mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>- Learn how to synthesize hardware from a
VHDL design <o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:1.0in'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p>The course is composed of two components: lectures and labs. The objective
of the lectures is to introduce and help you learn VHDL and CAD tools,
processor design and verification concepts. The lab has three objectives: learn
to program in VHDL and use the CAD tools, review logic design, and introduce
the design and verification of main processor components and of the complete
processor. The bulk of your work will be in the lab. </p>

<p><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Administivia</b>
<o:p></o:p></p>

<p><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal;mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Instructor</i>:<span
style='mso-tab-count:1'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Professor
A. Veidenbaum</p>

<p style='margin-left:.5in'>Office: 3056 Bren Hall</p>

<p style='margin-left:.5in'>Mail: alexv@ics</p>

<p style='margin-left:.5in'>Office Hours: Immediately after class or by
appointment.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p style='margin-left:.5in'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p>All lab assignments will be posted on the web and must be submitted electronically
on EEE. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p>Late assignments will NOT be accepted (exceptions for illness or other cases
may be made, <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>in
writing, </b>and submitted to the TA or instructor). </p>

<p>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>

<p><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>GRADING<o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p>Your grade in CS154 will depend on your performance in class and lab
assignments. The following approximate weights are going to be used:<o:p></o:p></p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal;mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Class attendance and participation - 10%. <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Class and lab attendance are mandatory </b><o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal;mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Lab - 90%<o:p></o:p></i></p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Individual lab assignments carry different weights depending on the degree
of difficulty, approximately 3/5/10/10/15/25. </p>

<p><br>
We'll try to grade the material as quickly as possible, but grading is not
instantaneous. </p>

<p>Lab assignment results will be posted online.</p>

<p>If you wish to have something re-graded, you MUST write a cover sheet and
hand it to the TA or the instructor. Explain why you believe a problem (or
problems) was mis-graded. The re-grades <u>will only be considered for a period
of 1 week </u>following the date of the result posting.</p>

<p>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>

<p><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Lab
Assignments (Tentative)<o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>Lab 1: Learn to use VHDL, make a simple design,
test it</p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>Lab 2: Design and verify a register file</p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>Lab 3: Design and verify a simple data path</p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>Lab 4: Add instruction fetch to the data path </p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>Lab 5: Add Ld/St, branches, to the data path </p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>Lab 6: Design a control unit for the data path (as
implemented in Lab 5), put together and verify the complete processor </p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'>Synthesis Lab&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>

<p style='margin-left:1.0in'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></b></p>

</div>

